<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / The Lex Column: Electricity
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The striking thing about the price deal announced yesterday between eight of
the UK's regional electricity companies and their regulator was the ease
with which it was reached. Clearly the RECs could teach the generators a
thing or two about keeping on the right side of the Office of Electricity
Regulation (Offer). Granted, Offer adopted a moderate position from the
outset last October, so the odds were always on the companies avoiding a
damaging confrontation. Yesterday's modest settlement on next year's price
increases means they will not have to compromise their progressive dividend
policies. Consumers have less reason to be pleased. But at least the
settlement means they will pay Pounds 35m less next year in compensation for
having been overcharged before.
Neither do the RECs have much to fear from Offer's remarks on the general
need to reduce the role of inflation forecasts in setting prices. The
implication seems to be that Offer would prefer to impose its own central
forecast. That might prove awkward if Offer were to err persistently on the
low side; but if so, it would bear the blame for subsequent price increases.
True to form, the RECs' shares barely reacted yesterday. Over the last year,
the shares have been moved principally by political sentiment. The curious
thing is that the sector's present yield premium to the market is not far
short of past peaks coinciding with Labour's largest leads in the opinion
polls. While the market is demanding such a wide degree of comfort, there
seems little additional investment risk attached to a Labour victory. If the
Tories were to be re-elected, the shares would be correspondingly cheap.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
