<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / International Capital Markets: OSE clamps down on
derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEW measures to dilute the impact of trading in Nikkei 225 stock futures and
options on the cash stock market were implemented yesterday by the Osaka
Securities Exchange, the second largest stock exchange in Japan.
Derivatives trading on the OSE has been blamed for the volatility in the
cash market. Alarmed authorities, especially those at the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, which has seen trading commissions plunge due to low volumes, have
been pushing for controls on derivatives trading.
The move comes at a time when tensions between the OSE and the TSE are
mounting. Trading in the Osaka-based Nikkei 225 futures index rose 2.7 times
last year, and accounted for 56.2 per cent of the OSE's trading revenue.
At the same time, revenue at the TSE plunged as small-lot investors have
become intimidated by the price fluctuations claimed to be created by
futures-linked arbitrage.
Traders said the OSE's move would not affect derivatives trading
drastically.
The closing time of futures and options trading is being shortened to match
the close in stock trading after criticism that speculative futures trading
after the stock market closed often affected prices on the following day.
New Japan Securities, a second-tier Japanese broker, said it would close
four domestic branches at the end of March.
Market report, Page 29
</TEXT>
