<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / International Company News: Continental submits debt plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONTINENTAL Airlines, the fifth largest US carrier, yesterday filed with the
bankruptcy courts a reorganisation plan which would involve unsecured
creditors swapping their claims for equity in the ongoing company.
The carrier has had talks with various possible merger partners and
potential investors over the past year - including Northwest Airlines and,
at a very preliminary level, with the now-bankrupt Trans World Airlines.
It said yesterday that the filing of the plan would not preclude a deal in
the future, and suggested that it might even induce some parties to enter
discussions. Continental added, however, that 'nothing is in the offing' at
present.
Under the scheme, existing ordinary and preferred shareholders would get
nothing. Subordinated debt would also be eliminated.
Continental said that obligations to secured debtholders would generally be
scaled down, and that the plan overall would reduce long-term liabilities
from around Dollars 5.8bn to Dollars 1.7bn. It estimated that the total
annual saving on interest and lease payments would be approximately Dollars
270m.
On the operational side, however, employees - around 43,000 people - and
flight operations would be little affected, Continental said.
The plan put forward by Continental, which filed for protection under
Chapter 11 of the US Bankruptcy Code in late 1990, has the support of the
Official Committee of Unsecured Creditors.
Some 50m shares of new common stock would be issued to the unsecured
creditors, with the company having the initial authorisation to issue up to
200m shares of common stock and 100m preferred shares.
Continental noted, however, it had not reached agreement with the Pension
Benefit Guaranty Corporation over its possible responsibilities towards
Eastern Airlines, the now-defunct carrier which was once a sister
organisation.
It said that the PBGC was asserting a 'priority claim' which, if successful,
would leave very little for the unsecured creditors.
It added an optimistic note, saying that 'results in January and bookings
for the next several months support our belief that the recent progress will
be continuing'.
</TEXT>
