<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Bass files lawsuit over Holiday Inn buy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BASS, the brewery and leisure group, has filed a lawsuit in the US federal
courts, claiming that it was misled about the condition of the Holiday Inn
chain, which it acquired for Dollars 2.23bn two years ago.
The lawsuit, in which Bass seeks unspecified damages, is thought to allege
that Promus, the US-quoted casinos and hotels company which remained once
Holiday Corporation's Holiday Inn business had been sold off to Bass, misled
the group about the condition of many hotels, the nature of their leases and
their compliance with various laws, including zoning compliances.
Further allegations are understood to centre on potential liabilities at
Holiday Inn which Bass claims it did not know about at the time of merger.
It also claims that Promus is not adhering to the terms of a tax sharing
agreement concerning pre-merger taxes on Holiday Inn hotels.
Holiday Inn last night declined to discuss details of the lawsuit, but
confirmed that it had been filed. There was no immediate response from
Promus.
Holiday Inn has been described as the world's largest hotel brand. At
end-1990 it took in about 1,600 hotels and approximately 320,000 rooms in 48
countries.
At Bass's annual meeting last month, Mr Ian Prosser, chairman, told
shareholders that economic conditions in some parts of the US had continued
to depress occupancy rates in some company-managed hotels, but that this had
been partially offset by higher room rates.
</TEXT>
