FT  07 FEB 92 / Wace launches inquiry into Clegg years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, PHILIP GAWITH, JIMMY BURNS and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WACE GROUP said yesterday it had launched a 'wide-ranging inquiry' into all
aspects of the company during the eight years Mr John Clegg built it into
the world's largest pre-press printing specialist.
Mr Clegg resigned as chief executive last Friday after speculation had
linked the company to the Irish Republican Army. Security sources said they
had uncovered no evidence of such links.
Mr Clegg denied the allegations but told the board last week that potential
future speculation would focus on his family, making it embarrassing to the
company for him to continue on its board.
Senior executives within the group, under pressure from shareholders, are
understood to be anxious to prepare a full response to the continuing
uncertainty about the company. They have broadened their investigations to
include members of Mr Clegg's family.
'It is absolutely vital to insure that no misconduct took place,' Mr Brian
Dudley, who succeeded Mr Clegg as managing director last week, has written
in a memo to the group's employees.
One area under scrutiny concerns the source of money Mr Clegg used to buy
into Wace in 1983 when it was a small loss-making shell company. He has
repeatedly said since then that he was backed by his cousin, Miss Jayne
Wright, who had inherited wealth and had emigrated to South Africa.
The company has established little about her so far but most of her
shareholding in Wace was sold in late 1988 for about Pounds 8m.
Mr Clegg offered at last week's board meeting to 'produce Miss Wright within
two weeks', according to a senior Wace executive. He resigned during the
meeting and has not been available for comment since.
Individuals connected with Wace have been the subject of investigations by a
number of authorities over the past year. These culminated in a meeting in
London last June attended by representatives of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary's C13 anti-racketeering squad, the Serious Fraud Office, the
Stock Exchange's Insider Dealing Group and the Bank of England.
These investigations followed earlier police inquiries in Sheffield where Mr
Clegg grew up.
Little about the Clegg family's South African connections have surfaced to
date. Mr Clegg's father, John senior, emerged last November as the purchaser
of 7m shares in Clegg Holdings, a South African paper and packaging company.
Mr Harry Clegg, chairman of Clegg Holdings, said he was no relation to the
Yorkshire Cleggs but he had met the son. He said his relationship with Mr
Clegg Snr dated back to 1987 when Clegg Holdings was listed. Mr Clegg Snr
had written a letter saying he was interested in investing in the company.
The holding stands at 23.3 per cent.
</TEXT>
