FT  07 FEB 92 / Institutions stand firm says Bank of Japan's governor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR YASUSHI MIENO, the governor of the Bank of Japan, said yesterday that the
end of Japan's speculative boom, together with the debts the period had left
behind, was 'very, very unlikely to shake the stability of financial
institutions'.
Nevertheless, the central bank had to keep a closer eye on financial
stability than it did before, he said in an interview with the Financial
Times.
Central banks had two goals: price stability and the stability of the
financial system. 'In the past, previous governors put a little more weight
on the maintenance of price stability (than on financial stability). But
under the current circumstances we should attach equal importance to these
two objectives'.
In a speech to Japanese businessmen later, he warned the US and Europe
against seeking rapid solutions to the problems of slow growth and
recession. Group of Seven countries should not resort to short-term policies
to promote growth at the expense of long-term sustainable growth, Mr Mieno
said.
Mr Mieno's remarks were seen as warning other G7 countries, particularly the
US, to avoid hasty cuts in interest rates or increasing public spending to
stimulate the economy.
Long-term economic adjustments were often difficult to carry out for
political reasons and tended to be postponed, Mr Mieno said, referring to
the need for the US to cut its federal deficit. But delay would leave
countries prey 'to the risk of excessively stimulating their economies'.
Mr Mieno also said that even though international policy co-ordination was
important, each country should pursue its own policies and not rely on other
G7 members to make short-term changes in their economic management for the
benefit of others. 'Instead of focusing unduly on short-term growth, we
should look at the growth fundamentals.'
Mr Triple Trouble fights his corner, Page 13
