<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Observer: Going a bomb
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Kuwait looks to have developed its own variant of Russian Roulette in the
shape of the '170 Rule' being bandied around by Kuwait City residents
jittery about renewed Iraqi attack.
Many have bought all-terrain vehicles in readiness for a fast escape across
the desert. The trouble is that the sands hide millions of mines and such
left from the Gulf war.
Hence the rule, based on the idea that if you hit the mines fast enough, you
are safely past them before they explode. 'Anything over 170km a hour and
you can watch them go off in your rear view mirror,' says one expatriate.
He has not yet tried it personally, however. Nor is it clear whether the
rule includes allowance for 10 per cent speedometer error.
</TEXT>
