<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Observer: Waiting on
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Despite all the fine talk about equal opportunity, women still stand a much
better chance of making it to the top in Britain's civil service than in Big
Business. Barbara Mills's switch from heading the Serious Fraud Office to
being the director Of public prosecutions is just the latest example.
By contrast, Anne Ferguson's appointment as a non-executive director of
National Power is less of a breakthrough. Like Yve Newbold, Hanson's company
secretary who has gone on to the BT board, the 49-year-old Ferguson has an
impressive record.
She has been responsible for modernising ICI's public persona. So her
experience should certainly help to add force to what National Power
surrealistically terms its 'invisible image'.
Nevertheless, her appointment once again raises the question of why women
are so rarely given executive directorships, as distinct from the
non-executive variety.
The response of Newbold and Ferguson, as loyal corporate types, is to say
that it won't be long before ICI and Hanson appoint women to fully fledged
directorships. But Observer is fast growing tired of waiting.
</TEXT>
