<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM warns of 'danger' in Scots
secession - News in brief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prime minister last night expressed confidence that Scots would reject
independence if the option were put to them at a referendum. He warned that
the prospect of an independent Scotland would be 'immensely dangerous'.
Questioned in an interview on BBC radio about a recent surge in support for
secession, Mr John Major reiterated his belief in the union with England and
Wales, saying that some Scots failed to recognise how much independence
would cost them.
When his interviewer argued that some 70 per cent of Scots now favoured some
form of devolution, Mr Major referred back to the surge in nationalism that
led to the plebiscite in 1979 on the creation of a national assembly. 'We
had a referendum once before,' he said. 'But when faced with the reality, it
melted away.'
The prime minister also rejected any comparisons between support for the
aspirations of newly independent states in eastern Europe and opposition to
Scottish nationalists.
The Act of Union had been entered into voluntarily and had been beneficial
for all parts of the UK, he said.
*****
RPI: New methods are being considered for the calculation of the retail
prices index to take account of the council tax when it replaces poll tax,
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said in a written Commons reply last
night.
The poll tax is included in the index with food prices, mortgage rates and
prices of leading goods.
Mr Lamont said the RPI advisory committee would also look at modifying the
index to take account of holiday expenditure and changes in new car prices,
and how it might be brought into line with similar indices in other European
countries.
*****
THIRD WORLD: The Conservative manifesto will include a warning that aid will
be cut for developing countries which failed to practice 'good government',
Mrs Lynda Chalker, overseas development minister, said yesterday.
She added: 'Where human rights are systematically abused, or where aid is
feeding corruption rather than mouths, we shall have no alternative but to
cut it.'
*****
BRITISH RAIL: Mr John Prescott, Labour transport spokesman, said last night
that if the government did not change BR financing arrangements so it could
buy new rolling stock, ministers would risk killing off Britain's rail
manufacturing industry.
</TEXT>
