<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: 'Green' measure of GDP propose -
Environment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW way of measuring national income which takes better account of
environmental factors - a 'green gross domestic product' - will be endorsed
next week by the Liberal Democrats.
Based on the idea of a 'sustainable net national income', it proposes that
some environmentally undesirable activities should count as minuses in
calculating gross domestic product (GDP), and that weight should be given to
'green' initiatives which are not included under the current measurements.
The party believes that it would take about five years to set up the system,
which could ultimately replace the existing one.
The system derives from a report, to be published next week, by Mr Roefie
Heuting, an environmental economist who advises the Dutch government. It
addresses the point that while cleaning up pollution counts as economic
activity and is thus included in the calculation of GDP, benefits from
initiatives such as investment in energy efficiency and low-energy
technology are not included.
By becoming the first party to commit itself to developing these plans, the
Liberal Democrats believe they can reinforce their high profile on
environmental issues.
Party officials believe there is some frustration among government
environmental advisers that little or no progress has been made on work in
this area, though there was some discussion of it when the white paper on
the environment was published in 1990.
Among the activities that the report proposes should be included in GDP
calculations are afforestation, a shift away from air traffic to greater use
of water and rail and the replacement of paper by electronic publication.
</TEXT>
