<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour urges pre-Budget incentives
 -Economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday called on the government to introduce investment incentives
for industry before next month's Budget as it sought to pin the blame for
the recession firmly on Conservative policies.
Its concerted attack included attempts to undermine the credibility of Mr
John Major, the prime minister, on economic issues and to cast doubt on the
government's ability to engineer a recovery. In particular, the assault
targeted the government's repeated contention that present economic
difficulties are worldwide.
The government responded by branding Labour gloom-merchants and asserting
that the worst of the domestic recession was over. Current policies would
help to produce low inflation, low interest rates and improved confidence,
which were the preconditions for a sustained recovery.
In another heated clash with the prime minister, Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour
leader, recalled that on Tuesday Mr Major wrongly included Japan among
countries whose economies were in recession. Mr Major was 'imagining
recovery at home while inventing recessions abroad'. He added: 'There are
economies that are slowing - ours is in reverse because of your policies.'
Mr Major said growth in Japan 'has slowed or is slowing'. He added that Mr
John Smith, the shadow chancellor, had now acknowledged the 'downturn' in
the world situation. He asserted that Labour's policies would result in
higher taxes and inflation, and lead to 'perpetual recession'.
At an earlier Labour press conference, Mr Gordon Brown, shadow trade and
industry secretary, had questioned the government's ability to steer the
economy out of the doldrums.
'It is because the prime minister cannot admit he is wrong that he cannot
take action to put the economy right,' he said, using a graph to indicate
how the government had repeatedly erred in its economic forecasts.
He challenged Mr Major to 'overrule the chancellor over investment
incentives now demanded' by industry in a series of Budget submissions.
The prime minister's 'claims about a worldwide recession' were simply an
attempt to 'shift the blame from the government's own responsibility for
economic failure'.
Mr Brown returned to this theme in a strongly-worded address in the Commons,
during which he stated 'there is no world recession' and claimed Mr Major
was condemned by his own words as economically illiterate.
Turning to the government's forecasting record, he compared Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, with the weatherman Mr Michael Fish. But whereas Mr
Fish was remembered for his mistake over predicting the 1987 hurricanes, the
chancellor was utterly reliable. 'He will always let you down,' he said.
Mr Brown sought to contrast the positive economic message produced by a
number of Tory-leaning newspapers with the more cautious words delivered to
shareholders by senior executives of the companies which owned the
newspapers. The truth was that the government was conjuring up a recovery
which did not exist with a publicity machine which did not even believe in
it, he said.
Mr Peter Lilley, trade and industry secretary, forecast that a Labour
election victory would be followed by a run on the pound, and challenged Mr
Brown to say how he would deal with the situation.
Would Labour put up interest rates to maintain the existing parity or would
it devalue, he asked. When Mr Brown did not respond, Mr Lilley said that
every Labour government had in fact done both.
Mr Kenneth Warren (C Hastings and Rye), chairman of the Commons trade and
industry committee, called on the chancellor to consider how to raise
returns on investment in manufacturing industry and criticised the tough
treatment of small business by banks.
A Labour motion condemning government economic mismanagement was defeated by
187 votes to 292.
</TEXT>
