<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tax lesson escapes many Tory
memories - Philip Stephens draws a parallel between this Budget and Sir
Geoffrey Howe's in 1981
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLITICIANS have short memories. As the Commons debated the recession
yesterday only a handful of Conservative MPs would admit that Mr Norman
Lamont should do anything but cut taxes in his Budget on March 10.
The orthodox wisdom on the government benches is that a pre-election boost
to the economy through lower income taxes would represent a perfect
coincidence of economic good sense and political advantage.
A Pounds 2bn or Pounds 3bn tax cut - and some Conservative MPs are now
suggesting that would be a modest reduction - would be entirely consistent
with the party's reputation for prudence, because of the depth of the
recession.
A jump in the public sector borrowing requirement to more than Pounds 20bn,
the argument runs, can be brushed off as simply a mirror image of the
economic cycle. It will gradually disappear naturally once the economy
returns to growth, in line with the policy of balancing the budget over the
medium term.
The fact that 1p off the basic rate of income tax or a sharp rise in
thresholds would also define the essential difference between the
Conservatives and Labour just before the election is no more than chance.
No one seems to remember 1981.
That was the year when Mrs Margaret Thatcher's first government was battling
with a similarly deep recession. Sir Geoffrey Howe, then chancellor, faced
intense pressure from the Opposition, from some in the cabinet, and from the
economics establishment to stimulate the economy by cutting taxes.
He did the reverse, putting them up by Pounds 3.6bn. The budget provoked a
storm of criticism culminating in its condemnation by 364 respected
economists. It sparked a debate about the role of fiscal policy which lasted
for most of the 1980s. If Mr Lamont followed Sir Geoffrey's example he would
put taxes up by about Pounds 7bn.
The parallels are striking. In the spring of 1981 it seemed that the economy
was locked in recession, but subsequent evidence showed that a recovery was
already under way. Mr Lamont insists the same will be true of this year. The
pound was then strong, although it was already slipping from its
extraordinary rise of the previous year. Inflation, as now, was falling
fast.
Ministers insist the differences are just as important. The government was
then following a money-supply target which included public borrowing as a
key component. That has been replaced by sterling's membership of the
Exchange Rate Mechanism, in theory a tighter constraint on cuts in interest
rates. (Few remember that the 1981 package was followed by a rise rather
than a cut in borrowing costs).
Sir Geoffrey was faced with a much higher structural budget deficit and a
substantially larger national debt than that confronting Mr Lamont.
The present chancellor can argue that large debt repayments during the 1980s
provide room for higher borrowing during a recession.
The few Conservative MPs whose memories stretch back to 1981 - and they tend
to be unreconstructed monetarists - are not convinced. They recall that once
it was clear that Sir Geoffrey's budget had not stifled the recovery,
ministers argued consistently that the rise in taxes had helped rather than
hindered the economy's emergence from recession.
Mr Nigel Lawson insisted repeatedly that attempts to influence the economic
cycle through fine-tuning of fiscal policy were inevitably misguided. He
stuck firmly to that principle when he cut taxes when the economy was
growing strongly. For most of Mr Lawson's tenure at the Treasury 'fiscal
stabilisers' was a proscribed phrase.
Now the government's supporters expect Mr Lamont to offer a seamless
justification for reducing the tax burden during a recession as well as in a
boom. But, as one survivor of that first administration recalls, there is
one essential difference between then and now.
Sir Geoffrey's package was unveiled two years rather than at most two months
before a general election.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
