FT  07 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Footwear workers accept pay freeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNION LEADERS representing 20,000 footwear workers yesterday accepted a
three-month pay freeze, as print employers said that they were also looking
for a pay deferral in negotiations covering their industry.
In a deal covering shoe manufacturing affiliates to the National Union of
Knitwear, Footwear and Apparel Trades, 20,000 employees will receive no pay
rise for three months from the March 9 settlement. Rates will rise by 3.75
per cent from June, and talks on a successor settlement will begin in
January.
The union said last month that an increase from March was a minimum
requirement for any deal. The employers had wanted a six-month freeze with a
3 per cent rise from September and cost-of-living-related rises in March and
September next year.
The British Printing Industries Federation told the GPMU print union that as
well as seeking a pay deferral it wanted wider wage differentials between
different groups of workers.
It also wants an agreement on integrated press rooms 'which would allow for
printing machines to be operated by a skilled and fully flexible workforce .
. . we will also wish to address the question of multi-skilling across craft
occupations'.
Mr Tony Dubbins, GPMU general secretary, said a freeze was totally
unacceptable.
