<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Shoring up the house of Ucatt / A look
at a union hit by defections and corruption
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUILDING union Ucatt is to make what could be a last bid for survival
when it announces a relaunch at the end of this month under its new general
secretary, Mr George Brumwell.
A series of events over the past year - including allegations of ballot
rigging, the suspension of the general secretary and mass defections of
officials to rival unions - have shaken the union to its foundations.
If the relaunch fails, Ucatt may finally find itself unable to resist
pressures to merge with another union.
A conference for full-time officials in three weeks will hear the grim truth
about the state of the union. Mr Brumwell is to spell out the need to halt
the decline in membership figures, eliminate corrupt practices, and
establish a new political direction for the union.
The latest chain of events may well be seen in future years as the start of
Ucatt's renaissance or the begining of its end. The process began in May
with a change of control in the union's executive.
It is misleading to define factions within Ucatt as 'right' or 'left' - what
can be said is that the members of the newly elected executive stood
together in wanting change.
Within a short time they had suspended Mr Albert Williams, who retires
officially next week as general secretary, and announced the setting up of
an independent inquiry under Mr John Hands QC into allegations of misconduct
during Mr Williams' tenure.
There followed the unedifying spectacle of Mr Williams, with financial
assistance from the Commissioner for the Rights of Trade Union Members,
battling with his own union in the High Court to retain his position. He was
eventually reinstated when it was proved that the suspension had not been
carried out according to Ucatt's own rule book.
The defections, which at one time threatened to engulf the entire union
movement in a row over poaching of members, boiled over in June during Mr
Williams' suspension. A total of 13 senior officials, many of them
frightened that they would be victimised by the new executive, left the
union.
Their first stop en masse was the GMB general union, where Mr John Edmonds,
GMB general secretary, offered what he said was a 'safe haven' to Ucatt
members and officials. Mr Edmonds argued that Ucatt faced 'virtual
disintegration and financial collapse'. The TUC was saved from having to
intervene publicly - and perhaps discipline its second-largest affiliate -
by the withdrawal of most of the GMB job offers to the ex-Ucatt officials.
All but two of the officials then turned to the non-TUC- affiliated EETPU
electricians' union. Since then, Ucatt's membership base has been under
attack from the rival union. Undoubtedly some damage was done to Ucatt by
the EETPU, although it is impossible to disentangle the propaganda put out
by both sides from the facts.
Ucatt officials feel the worst of the threat from the EETPU is now over.
Amalgamation talks between the EETPU and AEU engineering union have dampened
the electricians' ardour: the AEU strongly opposed the EETPU's poaching
moves and the TUC has indicated that it could not look on the merger
favourably if the EETPU continues such activities.
A stronger threat comes from the continued recession and the union's
dependence on 'check-off' for the collection of subscriptions: if there is
no work, union members are not having their union dues deducted from their
earnings. Membership has now dipped to just over 200,000 from a level of
240,000 in recent years; a Pounds 500,000 deficit last year could be
repeated again this year. Plans for the restructuring of the union and the
sale of property will be presented to the conference at the end of the
month.
The outstanding issue remains corruption and the long-awaited outcome of the
Hands inquiry - Ucatt's equivalent to the National Union of Mineworkers'
Lightman report. It now looks unlikely that ballot-rigging charges will be
substantiated. However, Hands will probably make recommendations about the
future conduct of elections and ways in which Ucatt's constitution should be
altered.
There could, for example, be a recommendation that branch balloting should
be replaced by postal voting and that candidates should be allowed openly to
campaign for election, instead of covertly, as often happens now.
Whatever the findings, officials are hoping the inquiry will be concluded
soon so that a clear line can be drawn under previous events before the
union's relaunch.
Amore difficult change for Mr Brumwell to implement will be a general
cleaning up of the way business is conducted. For the first time at the
conference officials will discuss a strategy for recruitment and be given
clear targets.
A package designed to attract self-employed building workers - who now
account for more than 700,000 of a 1.3m workforce - will be drawn up.
A new accountability will be spelled out: no longer will it be possible for
officials to wander around the country without anyone knowing where they
are. Relations with employers, which have frequently been too cosy, must be
cleaned up, Mr Brumwell will say.
As one insider put it: 'Officials will be told 'if you can eat and drink it
(what's being offered by a contractor), fine; if you can spend it, it's
not.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
