<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Subdued party fails to bury Ashdown
rumpus - Liberal Democrats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'IT'S business as usual,' was the refrain of the Liberal Democrats
yesterday, one day after Mr Paddy Ashdown's admission that he had an affair
with his former secretary five years ago. Inevitably, however, it was not.
Statements from the two women involved - Mr Ashdown's wife Jane and his
former secretary Ms Tricia Howard - together with an arrest in connection
with the theft of the document which led to Mr Ashdown's public admission,
meant the party could not put the matter behind it in a single day.
There was a strange silence as Mr Ashdown rose in his place in the Commons
yesterday afternoon to put a question to the prime minister. Either heckling
or murmurs of support had been variously expected. His call for co-operation
between politicians in Northern Ireland drew warm agreement from Mr John
Major, but Mr Ashdown looked tense and somewhat abstracted.
In a concerted effort to raise party morale Mr Ashdown gave a pep talk to
workers at the Liberal Democrat headquarters in Cowley Street yesterday
morning, while Mr Des Wilson, the party's campaign manager, wrote to those
involved in general election work expressing pride in Mr Ashdown's
leadership.
Colleagues said Mr Ashdown was 'in good heart', but the tone of party
managers was almost subdued.
On BBC radio Mr Charles Kennedy, Liberal Democrat president, seemed to imply
that lack of time was an element in any lack of change to the party's
campaign strategy.
Mr Wilson said that Mr Ashdown would remain at the head of the campaign. He
added that the plan was for a team of the younger MPs to have a high
profile. He had already approved a series of advertisements in which Mr
Ashdown did not feature, as he would be appearing extensively in news
coverage.
There was clearly some anger among Mr Ashdown's colleagues at the extensive
treatment of the story by some tabloid newspapers, which Mr Wilson accused
of trying to deliver a knock-out blow. 'They have failed,' he said
emphasising the flood of letters and telephone calls of support that the
party had received.
Mr Ashdown travelled to his Yeovil constituency last night, and prepared for
his local party's annual general meeting today. His next party engagement is
the launch on Tuesday of a campaign to get constitutional reform on to the
election agenda. By then, the party hopes, it really will be business as
usual.
</TEXT>
