<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Sony chief says accountants should not lead industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR AKIO MORITA, chairman of Sony Corporation, the Japanese electronics
group, last night challenged the way senior executives are promoted in
British industry by declaring that accountants should not run manufacturing
companies.
Mr Morita, originator of the Walkman portable stereo and other consumer
electronics products, was giving the first in a series of lectures on
innovation organised by the Department of Trade and Industry. The lectures
are intended to raise the profile of innovation within British industry.
He contrasted Japan, where almost every big manufacturing group is run by an
engineer or technologist, with Britain, where a significant proportion of
manufacturing companies are run by executives with a background in
accountancy.
Mr Morita said senior executives of a company had to be committed to
technology and engineering to promote innovation at lower levels.
'Here in the UK I am told some manufacturers are led by chief executives who
do not understand the engineering that goes into their own products,' he
said. 'Someone mentioned to me that many UK corporations are headed by
chartered accountants. This strikes me as very curious.'
Mr Morita continued: 'Though I have a great deal of respect for accountants
and financial professionals, I do not believe they should be at the helm of
industry.'
Successive studies of senior British management have found that more top
British industrialists have a background in finance and accountancy than
those in competitor countries such as Germany, France and Japan.
Mr Morita called on companies to give technologists higher status to combat
the widespread view that engineers are similar to mechanics.
He said: 'We must advance young technologists through the managerial ranks.
Manufacturing and high-technology corporations must be led by those who
understand not just business but technology as well.'
Letters, Page 13
</TEXT>
