<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Retailers warned of US discount threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RETAILERS were warned yesterday of a threat from 'warehouse clubs' which
have have had a 'devastating price impact' on traditional supermarkets in
the US.
Mr Tony MacNeary, an analyst at stockbrokers County NatWest, told a
retailing conference in London that Costco, one of the biggest US clubs,
planned to open two stores in the UK in the next 18 months.
The clubs, dubbed the 'silent enemy' in the US, sell a limited range of
deeply discounted goods from large, rudimentary stores. Shoppers are
required to join a 'club' to benefit from the low retail prices. More than
65 per cent of volume sales go to wholesalers.
Since 1985 the US clubs have increased food sales at an annual rate of 37
per cent, with gross margins of 8 per cent to 10 per cent compared with the
25 per cent enjoyed by traditional supermarkets.
The club sector in the US has expanded from four stores with total sales of
Dollars 275m in 1980 to 500 stores with Dollars 28bn of sales by last year.
'What the club stores in the US are inflicting on the traditional
supermarkets today could prove as momentous as the change bought about in
the industry in the 1950s,' Mr MacNeary said. That was when supermarkets
challenged the then-traditional stores.
International competition in the UK discount food market has recently
intensified with the arrival of the Aldi chain, from Germany, and Netto from
Denmark.
Mr Bob Willett, chief executive of Gateway, told the conference that the UK
supermarket group would open three more Food Giant superstores by April,
making 18 in all.
</TEXT>
