<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Four jailed over park fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOUR MEN were jailed and another was fined yesterday over the 1985 collapse
of the Britannia theme park at Shipley, near Heanor in Derbyshire, with
debts of Pounds 9.34m. At 17 months it was the UK's longest criminal trial.
Mr Peter Kellard, who controlled the company that built the theme park, was
jailed for four years and disqualified as a director for five years after
being found guilty earlier this week of 19 fraud charges.
The case covered charges of fraudulent trading, theft, deceit in order to
obtain bank loans and project finance, and the shuffling around of assets to
keep them out of the hands of a receiver and to provide funds for the
directors of KLF (UK), Mr Kellard's company, and its subsidiaries.
The jury at Nottingham Crown Court heard 158 prosecution witnesses and 28
defence witnesses and took seven days to decide its verdicts. Mr Kellard
gave evidence for 29 days.
The offences took place between 1980, shortly after KLF negotiated a lease
with Derbyshire County Council for the theme-park site, and September 1985,
when Samuel Montagu, the merchant bank which provided Pounds 3.7m of project
finance, called in Cork Gully as receiver.
In addition to Samuel Montagu there were 608 creditors, of which 203 were
Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire businesses owed up to Pounds 20,000 each.
Britannia Park was open in a half-finished state for three months before
Cork Gully was called in. Derbyshire police became involved in July 1986. It
was the largest fraud inquiry the force had undertaken and it cost nearly
Pounds 2m. The first arrests were made in 1987.
The Crown Prosecution Service said yesterday that its costs - fees for
counsel and other legal expenses but excluding staff costs - had come to
Pounds 1m.
The trial started in September 1990 with six defendants, one of whom, Mr
Keith Emmett, was cleared of the three charges he faced.
In addition to Mr Kellard, three other directors of KLF or its subsidiaries
were sentenced. Mr Edward Dwyer was jailed for 2 1/2 years and disqualified
as a director for five years on six charges. Mr John Wright was jailed for
six months and disqualified for three years on five charges. Mr Kenneth
Page, who pleaded guilty at the start of the trial, was jailed for six
months on five charges.
Mr Saied Sobhkhiz, the managing director of Bournemouth-based Euro-per &amp;
Gulf who changed his plea to guilty last year, was fined Pounds 7,500 and
ordered to pay Pounds 25,000 costs on two charges.
Cork Gully eventually sold Britannia Park to Derbyshire County Council for
Pounds 2.5m.
The park had been devised in the first place to honour British invention.
Now it exists as the American Adventure Theme Park.
</TEXT>
