<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Lloyd's chief outlines plans for shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DETAILS OF how Lloyd's of London plans to implement a series of far-reaching
reforms of the insurance market's structure were disclosed yesterday by Mr
Alan Lord, chief executive, who also confirmed his intention to resign in
June.
Uncertainty over the future governance of Lloyd's in the wake of the
publication last month of the report outlining the reforms has delayed the
appointment of a successor to Mr Lord, who is 62. His intention to resign
was announced last year.
When Mr Lord leaves, three senior executives, led by Mr John Gaynor, the
finance chief, will take control of day-to-day management of the corporation
with a new chief executive being introduced next year after all the working
groups examining the recommendations of the reform task force have reported.
The Lloyd's solvency committee chaired by Mr Richard Hazell, a leading
underwriter, will work on details of the scheme to limit the potential
losses of Lloyd's Names and will report to Lloyd's Council by the end of
April.
Work on the examination and implementation of the task force's 65 separate
recommendations will be carried out by groups appointed by the council.
Mr Hazell will chair a group examining members' agents pooling arrangements,
a new unit-trust type system for Names, which expects to report in the next
few months.
Five other groups will examine other task force recommendations covering:
the reduction of costs (chaired by Mr Brian Pomeroy); Names' rights (Sir
Maurice Hodgson); corporate capital (Mr John Greig); accessibility of Names'
capital (Mr Michael Cockell); and governance (Sir Jeremy Morse).
</TEXT>
