<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Amex may face action on Olympics advertising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN EXPRESS, the US financial services group, may face legal action
from this year's Winter Olympics organisers for allegedly 'ambush marketing'
the event. The games open tomorrow at Albertville in France.
Mr Dick Pound, chairman of the International Olympic Committee's marketing
commission, yesterday accused American Express of conducting an advertising
campaign implying it was an official sponsor of the games, which is not the
case.
One of the Olympics' main sponsors is credit card agency Visa, which with 12
other sponsors is paying about Pounds 170m towards the cost of staging the
games.
'The long-standing war between Visa and Amex continues, just like a Russian
novel - no beginning and no end in sight,' Mr Pound said.
American Express has taken magazine space and billboard posters in
Albertville for slogans such as 'Amex at the Games.'
Mr Pound said the Amex campaign was 'trying to undercut' Visa.
He declined to comment on how much Visa was paying to sponsor the games but
it is believed to be in the region of about Dollars 20m.
Mr Frank Vaccaro, American Express's director of public affairs
(international), said yesterday his company was 'aware of reports of legal
action being taken by the IOC but as yet we have not seen anything and have
not been officially informed of any pending legal action.'
Mr Vaccaro accused Visa of conducting a 'months-long' comparative US
advertising campaign, attacking American Express by suggesting visitors to
the Games should leave their Amex cards at home.
</TEXT>
