<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Croatians fall into line on UN peace plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CROATIA'S President Franjo Tudjman has dropped objections to the United
Nations peace plan for Yugoslavia, the Security Council was told last night.
Croatia had been insisting that UN troops be deployed in such a way that it
would leave open the prospect of recovering the third of its territory now
under the control of the federal army and Serb irregulars.
Mr Thomas Pickering, the council's US president, said Mr Milan Babic, leader
of the Serb-populated region of Krajina in Croatia, now was the only
objector to the UN plan.
He said Mr Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general, felt the time was not
ripe to deploy a large UN peace-keeping force, as proposed by Mr Cyrus
Vance, the UN special envoy.
Mr Vance said he had received the Croatian leader's assurances after seeking
clarification of a communication from Zagreb on Monday.
He praised the 'most helpful' intervention of Mr Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the
German foreign minister, in bringing this about.
The UN envoy repeated his belief that Germany had been premature in
recognising independent Yugoslav republics.
'Given the extremely delicate situation which exists at this time, . . . I
would think it very unwise for any further outside parties to disturb the
present situation by recognising any of the republics.'
Mr Vance said the federal government and army and other leaders were
pressing Mr Babic hard to accept the UN plan.
Asked about the possibility of sending in an interim UN peacekeeping force
smaller than the 10,000 men envisaged, Mr Vance said it was too early to go
ahead with other than a modest addition of 25 liaison officers to the 50
already there.
Laura Silber in Belgrade adds: Lord Carrington, the European Community
envoy, yesterday said the leaders of Bosnia-Hercegovina had agreed to hold
an EC-brokered conference in an attempt to dilute rising nationalist
tensions. After talks in Sarajevo, he said Slavic Moslem, Serb and Croat
leaders had agreed to his proposal for a conference of the republic's main
national groups before an independence referendum set for February 29 and
March 1.
</TEXT>
