<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / Tories and Labour still neck and neck
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIERCEST period of pre-election campaigning in recent memory has still
failed to give either of the two main political parties their much-sought
breakthrough, according to a batch of opinion polls released last night.
As the conviction grows at Westminster that Mr John Major will not duck an
April 9 election, there was nothing in the findings to convince either party
that they can be confident of an overall majority.
The first soundings on voters' reaction to Mr Paddy Ashdown's revelation of
an affair with his former secretary five years ago also suggested that the
scandal may have little effect in the polling booths.
While the Tories are taking comfort in figures showing them ahead, Labour
will argue that the government's month-long assault on its tax and spending
plans have used up its best shots without winning a decisive advantage.
Today, the focus switches to local government with Mr Michael Heseltine, the
environment secretary, attacking the records of Labour councils and Mr Neil
Kinnock, the Labour leader, highlighting the poll tax as the key 'symbol' of
Tory waste in a keynote speech to a Labour's conference in Blackpool.
On Saturday, the prime minister will deliver his riposte at the annual Young
Conservatives' rally in Eastbourne. But in spite of the frenzied atmosphere
in Westminster, public opinion remains equivocal.
A Gallup 'snapshot' poll for The Daily Telegraph, conducted between January
29 and February 3, gives the Tories 42.5 per cent or five points ahead of
Labour - a sharp turnabout on last week's 1.5 point Labour lead but a close
reflection of the same poll's findings in mid-January.
However, in the much larger Gallup 9000 poll, carried out throughout January
from a sample of nearly 11,000, Labour has pulled ahead by a statistically
insignificant 0.2 points to 39.2 points - its first lead in this survey for
four months.
That second verdict appeared to be reflected in the findings of a Harris
poll of 1,097 voters for The Daily Express. Conducted over the past two
days, it has Labour in a one-point lead on 40 per cent (unchanged on last
month) with the Tories dropping back to 39 (41).
The three polls put Liberal Democrat support varying from 14 (Gallup
snapshot) to 17 (Harris).
In a separate telephone poll on voters' reaction to Mr Ashdown's revelation,
Gallup found that 82.6 per cent supported his continuing as Liberal Democrat
leader, with only 4.6 per cent arguing that he should resign.
The polls came as Labour launched a series of onslaughts on the government's
economic record.
At question time, Mr Kinnock attacked Mr Major's claims this week that the
Japanese economy faced recession, saying that a slowdown was not the same as
the state of the UK's economy, now 'in reverse'. He added: 'The prime
minister, because of his policies, is reduced to imagining recovery at home,
while inventing recession abroad.'
Mr Major replied that Labour's policies would replace low taxation and low
inflation with high tax rates and high inflation and would reverse the best
industrial relations record Britain had enjoyed for half a century.
