<HEADLINE>
FT  07 FEB 92 / London Stock Exchange: Oils to telecoms switch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, COLIN MILLHAM, JOEL KIBAZO, STEVE THOMPSON and CHRISTOPHER
PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in BT and BP, the UK's second and third biggest companies as measured
by market capitalisation, moved in opposite directions as dealers reported a
switch out of the UK oil group and into the telecoms giant.
The Seaq ticker confirmed extraordinarily heavy turnover in the two
companies and provided evidence of two exceptionally large individual trades
in the stocks. The first was a line of 6.7m BP at 270 1/2 p, and the second
a block of 9m BT at 337p.
Speculation in the market suggested that County NatWest had executed the
deals on behalf of a big institutional client; County would not comment on
the switch story. The big switch, it was said, was part of a general
re-shaping of the investment portfolio of one of the UK's most powerful
institutions.
By the close of trading BT 'old' shares were 3 1/2 ahead at 334 1/2 p, after
337p, on heavy turnover of 8m shares, while the 'new' edged up 1 1/2 to
124p, after 125 1/2 p, with 14m traded. Also driving BT stock higher was the
recent Warburg Securities 'buy' recommendation and hints that one of the
analysts most bearish of BT in recent months, had lifted his 'sell' stance
on the stock.
BP shares, weakened over recent weeks by worries about the dividend cover,
weak oil prices and hints of a boardroom rift, slipped to 273p, before
stabilising and closing a net 2 1/2 off at 276p; turnover in BP totalled 18m
shares.
C &amp; W weaker
Telecoms group Cable &amp; Wireless (C &amp; W) delivered one of the poorest
individual performances among the Footsie stocks after Barclays de Zoete
Wedd, the investment bank, chopped its profits forecast for the company. C &amp;
W shares closed 13 lower at 580p, with 4.8m traded.
C &amp; W was also included by BZW in a list of leading UK companies which may
be affected by proposals put forward by the Accounting Standards Board,
although BZW was at pains to point out that this had nothing to do with its
profits downgrades.
BZW reduced its forecast of profits for the year ended March 1992 from
Pounds 720m to Pounds 695m and its estimate for the year ended March 1993
from Pounds 790m to Pounds 765m. The broker cited disappointing trading at C
&amp; W's Mercury division which it said was suffering from the impact of price
reductions last year and slowing volume gains. However, the investment bank
emphasised it was retaining its 'hold' stance on the stock.
Vickers sold
Vickers tumbled after Smith New Court reduced its dividend forecast. The
mid-morning reduction caused a 'backwardation' - a situation in which the
bid and offer price are temporarily reversed, leaving the shares 16 off at
160p. The broker said it expects the full-year dividend to total 5p, down
from its previous estimate of 6p and against the previous year's total of
9.9p.
Mr Chris Avery, at Smiths believes the company is running out of time for
the partial disposal of its Rolls-Royce Motors subsidiary before the
company's full-year figures are reported on February 24, a move he believes
would have assisted the dividend pay-out.
But sources close to the company later indicated to the market that the
dividend was likely to be nearer 5.9p. This helped Vickers rally off the
bottom to end 10 down at 166p on a hefty turnover of 3.8m.
Stores were generally firm, but Great Universal 'A' (GUS) gave up most
gains, closing 2 up at 1430p. At one time the shares were 50 higher at
1478p, amid suggestions that Cazenove, the company broker, was trying to buy
shares in an already illiquid market, and had recommended the stock after a
visit to one of the company's divisions on Wednesday. The rise also
reflected optimism ahead of a presentation given for GUS by Warburg
Securities, but this disappointed and was described as something of a
non-event.
Sears were particularly active, rising 2 to 102p. Smith New Court recently
recommended the shares as a good recovery stock, but regarded yesterday's
movement as simply a reflection of the sectors general strength. Marks &amp;
Spencer put on 5 to 304p, following a Kleinwort Benson recommendation.
Discount supermarket group Kwik Save fell 32 to 594p after James Capel cut
its profit forecast by Pounds 7m to Pounds 110m for the year to August 31
and by Pounds 12m to Pounds 122m for the following year. Kwik Save made a
trading profit of Pounds 101.7m last year. Increased price competition from
new operators in the discount food sector was behind the profit downgrade.
Vodafone sped up 9 to 353p on good turnover of 2.7m, mirroring strong gains
in cellular stocks on Wall Street. Smith Barney, the Wall Street brokerage,
was said to have shifted from a hold to a buy on Vodafone.
Standard Chartered raced up 9 to 420p in response to vague takeover stories
while talk of a UBS Phillips &amp; Drew recommendation was said to have lifted
Midland 3 1/2 to 230p. Lloyds Abbey Life was a notable weak spot in life
assurances, the shares losing 14 to 380p after a bearish recommendation from
Nomura, the Japanese-owned brokerage.
Commercial Union retreated 8 to 455p after reports that BZW had cut its 1992
dividend forecast and increased its estimate of 1992 losses.
Dollar weakness put pressure on internationally traded pharmaceuticals
stocks and a negative press report yesterday gave the excuse to take
profits. The newspaper article quoted a consumers' association study which
was critical of over-the-counter cold and influenza medicines.
SmithKline Beecham, which makes Beecham's Powders, fell 7 to 961p, Reckitt &amp;
Colman which manufactures Lemsip dropped 4 to 674p and Wellcome, which
produces a number of cough and cold remedies, slipped 12 to 1114p.
Glaxo responded to US selling and lost 18 to 829p and Fisons shed 6p to
379p.
Medeva gained 9 to 292p on the back of a presentation at US brokerage house
Merrill Lynch, by the chairman, Mr Bernard Taylor, to investors in New York.
Trading in Reuters Holdings was volatile following a significant share
placing which prompted a sharp slide on Wednesday. The company was, early
yesterday, rumoured to be suggesting that analysts' estimates of profits to
be announced next week were too high and the fall continued until the shares
were 20 off. Then, they proved oversold and bounced back to close only a
penny off at 1097p with 1.1m traded.
BTR was active in early dealing on concern that its Australian unit, BTR
Nylex, may write down the value of assets.
The shares closed only a penny off at 408p, after 403, with 3.6m traded.
BOC rose 10 to 648p against the trend as Kleinwort Benson published an
internal note restating its buy stance on the stock. The securities house
believes the company is on 'an undemanding rating'.
Babcock was active, the day's turnover reaching 12m and the shares remained
unchanged at 56 1/2 p. Tomkins fell 4 to 435p. The word in the market is
that the company is taking another look at Racal Electronics subsidiary,
Chubb.
Profit taking hit Inchcape, leaving the shares 9 down at 423p.
British Airways fell 4 to 230p, with Goldman Sachs reported to have been
offering stock at 231p. Smith New Court advised investors to take profits
and the shares were also said to have suffered from worries about the
company's accountancy methods included in a report from BZW.
Senior Engineering retreated 2 1/2 to 69 1/2 p after announcing a Pounds
26.6m rights issue.
Shares in Euro Disney firmed on reports in the French press that bookings
were well ahead of expectations. After rising to 1530p, the shares eased to
close 5 ahead at 1525p.
USM-quoted ice cream manufacturer Clarke Foods jumped 15 to 88p in the old
shares and 15 in the nil-paid to 27p after positive comment in a specialist
tip-sheet.
