FT  07 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two of BBC2's current Top 3 are Friday night repeats: the mid-sixties puppet
series Thunderbirds (6.00) and Victoria Wood - As Seen On TV (9.00).
Both are getting more than five million viewers whereas series such as '40
Minutes' and 'The Money Programme' are now languishing below the two million
mark. BBC2's social affairs series, Public Eye (8.00) has also failed to set
the Thames on fire, though its subjects are often significant. Today it
investigates the police disciplinary system, asking whether it deals
effectively with officers who break the law, or protects them from the
consequences of their actions; last year barely one in 20 complaints against
the police was upheld.
As usual on Fridays there are several movies. Slither (11.20 BBC1) is a bit
like much modern art: you need to know a lot about other pictures before you
can really appreciate all its jokes, influences and references. Mainly it is
a pastiche road movie. Astonishingly, A Strange Place To Meet (12.05 BBC2)
is also a parody of a road movie, this time French ('Slither' is American)
and much slower. Abba The Movie (12.05 C4) is like a 90-minute video for the
group, made in 1977.
</TEXT>
