<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / World Bank approves Dollars 300m loan for Peru
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE World Bank has approved a Dollars 300m (Pounds 165.7m) loan to Peru to
assist in the refinancing of the country's total foreign debt of about
Dollars 22bn.
The credit, the first of a series totalling Dollars 900m, comes much sooner
than expected.
The loan will not be physically disbursed, since it is part of an internal
accounting mechanism - similar to the 'rights accumulation' scheme employed
by the International Monetary Fund - to cover Peru's Dollars 900m arrears
with the World Bank. Once the total amount has been approved, Peru will be
eligible for fresh credits. The early decision on the loan demonstrates
World Bank approval of the speed of economic reform under President Alberto
Fujimori. Since Mr Fujimori took office 18 months ago, import tariffs have
been dramatically reduced and simplified, export subsidies ended and state
monopolies and trade controls eliminated.
The World Bank credit is repayable over 20 years with five years grace.
It is at a variable interest rate, currently around 7.7 per cent.
In what is being interpreted locally as a further sign of support and
approval on the part of the international financial organisations, Mr Michel
Camdessus, managing director of the IMF, will visit Lima next week.
President Fujimori, due to begin a visit to London today, says his economic
programme and anti-guerrilla strategy will defeat a Maoist insurgent
movement, Reuter reports from London.
'Return to the world financial community, the relative success of our
anti-inflation programme, structural reforms to make the state more
efficient and re-estabishment of a sense of authority are achievements which
mark a defeat for terrorists who fanatically seek to create chaos,' Mr
Fujimori said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
