<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / International Company News: LTV net improves, but operating
loss deepens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LTV, the US steel, aerospace and energy group which has been living for five
years under the protection of the bankruptcy courts, yesterday reported a
deepening of fourth-quarter operating losses, which it blamed on the US
recession.
LTV reported a net loss of Dollars 8.5m, or 12 cents a share, an improvement
on the loss of Dollars 19.5m, or 23 cents, reported in the same period of
1990. Sales dipped from Dollars 1.6bn to Dollars 1.52bn.
In the full year, it made Dollars 74.1m on sales of Dollars 5.99bn, compared
with income of Dollars 70.9m on sales of Dollars 6.14bn in 1990.
However, the figures were flattered by a third-quarter income tax refund of
Dollars 129.7m and related fourth-quarter interest income of Dollars 53.3m.
At the operating level, it lost Dollars 56.3m in the final quarter, up from
Dollars 25.9m a year ago.
Its steel operations reported a fourth-quarter operating loss of Dollars
54m, up from Dollars 11.1m, due to lower prices and shipments and higher
wage costs. Its energy products business produced a loss of Dollars 16.3m,
compared with a profit of Dollars 1.4m, mainly because of charges for excess
or slow-moving inventory.
However, its aerospace and defence business, which LTV agreed this week to
sell to a joint venture between Lockheed and Martin Marietta, produced
operating income of Dollars 14m, up from Dollars 8.8m in the final quarter
of 1990.
LTV has been involved in years of difficult negotiation with its creditors
and the federal Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation over the terms of a
restructuring which could bring it out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy.
It said yesterday it intended to file a new plan of reorganisation on
February 14, and that it had made 'substantial progress' toward bringing
creditor groups to agreement.
