FT  06 FEB 92 / International Company News: Miniscribe bondholders win
Dollars 550m in damages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TEXAS jury has awarded more than Dollars 550m in damages to former
bondholders of Miniscribe, the now defunct disk drive manufacturer.
The investors had accused Miniscribe's former chairman, as well as its
accounting firm and investment bankers, of fraud.
The defendants were found guilty of fraud and negligence and ordered to pay
punitive damages. The suit was filed by Kemper Management, representing
investors who had bought about Dollars 20m in Miniscribe bonds.
Mr Q. T. Wiles, chairman of Miniscribe during the period of the alleged
fraud, was ordered to pay Dollars 250m.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the international accounting firm, was ordered to pay an
additional Dollars 200m; damages against Hambrecht &amp; Quist, the San
Francisco investment banking group of which Mr Wiles is a former vice
chairman, were assessed at Dollars 45m. Mr William Hambrecht, chairman of
Hambrecht &amp; Quist, was ordered to pay Dollars 35m.
All the defendants said they would appeal against the verdict and damages
award. The judge has given them until next week to file arguments before he
approves or revises the jury's award.
The judgment is the first in connection with several pending lawsuits which
followed the bankruptcy of Miniscribe in 1990.
