FT  06 FEB 92 / International Company News: General Re climbs despite
lacklustre fourth quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Re, the largest reinsurance company in the US, yesterday reported an
increase in after-tax profits for the year, to Dollars 656.7m from Dollars
613.6m, although operating income excluding realised gains had been static.
The fourth-quarter advance in net profit was from Dollars 155.5m in 1990 to
Dollars 184.2m.
This figure for the final 1991 quarter was described as 'unsatisfactory' by
General Re, but it added that the figure would have been only 'marginally
so' had the big Oakland, California, fire not occured.
General Re said its underwriting results had fallen 'short of our goals',
but pointed out that they compared favourably with the rest of the
reinsurance industry.
The combined underwriting/expense ratio for the year increased from 99 per
cent to 102 per cent, year-on-year, and in the fourth quarter alone reached
103 per cent.
Operating income for the year, excluding realised gains, amounted to Dollars
561.8m, compared with Dollars 566m, with the fourth quarter showing a small
improvement at Dollars 147.6m, against Dollars 146.8m.
Revenues during the year increased slightly from Dollars 2.95bn to Dollars
3.2bn
Shares in General Re, known to be operating in a weak reinsurance market,
closed Dollars 1 7/8 higher at Dollars 95 1/8.
