FT  06 FEB 92 / International Company News: Berlusconi advances La Cinq bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Silvio Berlusconi, the controversial Italian media mogul, yesterday
cleared the first hurdle in his campaign to take charge of La Cinq, the
bankrupt French television channel, when his FFr1.5bn (Dollars 270m) rescue
plan was referred by La Cinq's judicial administrator to the Paris
commercial court.
The Berlusconi rescue package involves injecting FFr1.5bn of new capital
into the station, which filed for bankruptcy earlier this year, in two
tranches of FFr700m and FFr800m.
Mr Berlusconi, who currently owns 25 per cent of La Cinq, then intends to
cut costs - by reducing the workforce from 910 to 613 - in an attempt to
make the channel profitable.
Mr Hubert Lafont, La Cinq's administrator, has been studying the Berlusconi
bid since Monday. The proposals from two other would-be white knights -
Vogue, the French record company, and an unknown individual - were rejected
as unsuitable.
However, the Berlusconi rescue still faces a number of obstacles. First, the
Tribunal de Commerce, the Paris commercial court, will study it to see
whether it is financially viable. Second, the Conseil Superieur de
l'Audiovisuel, the body that regulates the French broadcasting system, must
decide whether it will enable La Cinq to fulfil its remit.
Meanwhile, the Berlusconi camp must press ahead with the financial
arrangements for the proposed recapitalisation. A general assembly of La
Cinq's shareholders will be held in two weeks to vote on the first capital
increase with the second recapitalisation following two months later.
Mr Berlusconi has said that Fininvest, the company through which he holds
his La Cinq stake, is committed to reinvesting in La Cinq.
</TEXT>
