the late Mr Robert Max-well, Mr Kevin Maxwell's father.
The affidavit arrived at 9pm at Mr Cooper's offices at Robson Rhodes, the
accountancy firm, although the court had ordered its deli-very by 'close of
busi-ness'.
Last week Mr Kevin Maxwell lost his appeal against the December judgment of
Mr Justice Hoffmann that he must answer Robson Rhodes' questions about the
operation of BIM.
Mr Maxwell had been arguing that he had a common law right to remain silent
to avoid self-incrimination, but this was rejected as it was ruled that the
Insolvency Act, under which BIM brought its claim, abrogated this privilege.
BIM was the manager and investment trustee of a common investment fund of
about Pounds 700m established for the pension funds of many of the companies
in the collapsed business em-pire of the late Mr Robert Maxwell.
