<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / The Lex Column: Car dealers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The market's verdict on the Monopolies and Mergers Commission report on the
motor trade was that while it could have been a lot worse, there is no great
rush to buy the sector. Car dealers may have escaped a radical shake-up of
the sort inflicted on the brewing industry. But there is no escaping the
recession, hence the modest reaction in the distributors' shares. Inchcape
was an exception, but that is probably accounted for as much by its recent
acquisition of Tozer Kemsley &amp; Millbourn as by the proposed relaxation of
import restrictions on Japanese cars. Its Toyota franchise means it should
benefit more than most, if only because it can concentrate on importing the
most lucrative models while Toyota will produce its cheaper cars in the UK.
More generally, the prospect of multiple-franchise dealerships remains
sufficiently distant for there to be little reason to mark up share prices
now. In the medium term, dealers are as vulnerable as ever to manufacturers'
tendency to grab back franchises once they become seriously profitable.
</TEXT>
