<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / ICI to be salt seller in Pounds 40m mine deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPERIAL Chemical Industries abandoned another part of its history in
pursuit of modern profit yesterday when it announced the sale of Britain's
only salt mine.
The mine, at Winsford, Cheshire, dates from 1844. It is being sold to an
investor group led by US-based D. George Harris &amp; Associates which is also
buying ICI's salt plant at Weston Point, Cheshire.
The operations are to be named Salt Union but the new owners hope to avoid
the fate of the first Salt Union founded on the site in 1888 with the aim of
creating a salt cartel.
The first Salt Union flopped, despite raising Pounds 3.7m in what was then
the City's largest rights issue. It paid only one ordinary dividend - in
1896 - and after 1898 had an unfortunate habit of passing the preference
dividend. It was acquired by ICI in 1937.
Told about the chequered history of the Salt Union, Mr William Sichko,
vice-president of human resources of the US operations of D. George Harris &amp;
Associates, said: 'We'll certainly be aiming to improve on their results. We
picked the name, not the legacy.'
Although the new company is the largest salt business in the UK, Mr Sichko
said there was no intention to emulate the old cartel. The acquisition,
which the groups hope to complete by the spring, is not subject to
regulatory approval.
The modern businesses, unlike their predecessor, are profitable, according
to ICI, which will receive Pounds 40m from the US buyer. The operations have
an average annual turnover of Pounds 45m.
ICI said the salt businesses, which employ about 200 people, fall outside
the group's long-term strategy of developing operations in which it has
strong global positions.
The rock salt mine at Winsford is about 150 feet deep and covers 1,255 acres
served by 100 miles of underground roadways. It fulfils two-thirds of the
demand for road de-icing salt in the UK.
The Weston Point operations supply some white salt for human consumption but
most of its output is used by the chemical industry.
ICI is acquiring Dow Chemical's brake fluid business in Europe, Africa and
the Middle East for an unspecified sum. Dow is buying ICI's coolant
businesses in the same regions.
</TEXT>
