<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour accuses SNP of 'toytown
economics' - Scottish Separatism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday launched a strong counter-attack on the Scottish National
party, with Mr Donald Dewar, the shadow Scottish secretary, accusing it of
'toytown economics' and 'blatant fraud' in putting the case for Scotland's
becoming independent.
Mr Dewar's attack, which was dismissed by the SNP as 'blind panic', is part
of Labour's attempt to head off what it fears will be a surge in support for
the nationalists, prompted by last week's opinion poll showing that 50 per
cent of Scots wanted some form of independence.
Last weekend a separate poll showed a drop of 9 points to 38 per cent in
support for Labour in Scotland compared with a month before, with the SNP up
5 points at 26 per cent.
Mr Dewar said the SNP was being dishonest in claiming that living standards
in Scotland would immediately improve with independence. 'There is no
certainty that we would be able to maintain the level of public services and
infrastructure that Scotland needs' with independence, he said.
Revenue from North Sea oil, on which many of the SNP's economic calculations
were based, was in relative decline and now yielded less than 1 per cent of
the total tax take in Britain.
'It is madness to float a major constitutional change on the basis of wildly
optimistic assumptions about an inevitably time-limited asset,' he said.
If there were a differential in interest rates between Scotland and England,
what would stop capital flowing south, Mr Dewar asked. 'Investors from what
was Britain will indeed come to Scotland but for cheap loans and nothing
else.'
In the short term, people working for Scottish defence contractors such as
Yarrow shipbuilders and GEC Ferranti would risk losing their jobs. UK Civil
Service departments that have been relocated to Scotland would be withdrawn,
he said.
'Scotland is not a country incapable of sustaining independence,' he said.
'Labour argues it would not be the best way forward.'
The government refused to be committed to a firm date for establishing a
Scottish further education funding council in the Commons last night.
Mr Michael Forsyth, Scottish Office minister of state, said it would be
wrong to to go beyond introducing a new clause to the Further and Higher
Education (Scotland) Bill giving the government freedom to decide when such
a body should be set up.
Although he described the new provision as a 'concession' to views expressed
by Labour MPs at an earlier stage of the bill, the opposition front benches
questioned its value.
Mr Anthony Worthington, a Labour frontbench spokesman, asked: 'Is this a sop
or an indication that the minister has accepted the case for a funding
council?'
Mr Forsyth told him: 'If we through a funding council would be entirely
inappropriate we would never have put this provision in the bill.'
He denied that the government planned to merge the further education funding
council with the higher education funding council.
A Labour amendment seeking to ensure that the Scottish further education
funding council would be established on April 1 1994 was defeated by 254
votes to 178, a government majority of 76.
</TEXT>
