FT  06 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Abolition of student loans proposed
by Lib Dems - Higher Education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INCREASE in investment in higher education, a doubling of student numbers
by the end of the decade and immediate abolition of the government's student
loans scheme were proposed by the Liberal Democrats yesterday.
In a new policy statement, the party calls for an independent pay review
body to give lecturers pay comparability with other professionals. It also
advocates the introduction of more flexible degree courses.
The Liberal Democrats also propose to abolish parental contributions to
students' living costs and to restore their rights to social security
benefits - both with heavy cost implications.
'The doors to higher education need opening far wider, giving access to all
sections of British society,' said Mr Matthew Taylor, the party's education
spokesman.
