FT  06 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Cook alleges cash fears in trust
hospitals - Health
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROBIN COOK, shadow health secretary, yesterday accused the government of
'cynically manipulating' information on the hospitals' financial status.
His attack came as Labour rounded on the government's health service
policies, using a leaked document it said showed 'worrying' financial crises
at a number of trust-status hospitals.
He said the document, from the National Health Service's management
executive, indicated that 86 NHS trusts and directly managed hospitals were
running up deficits of more than Pounds 100,000. Some were reaching millions
of pounds.
'Most of them are being forced to clear this deficit within two months by
slamming the brakes on patient care,' Mr Cook said.
Mr William Waldegrave, health secretary, reacted angrily at the use of
'stolen' documents for party political advantage. He said it was 'nonsense'
to use figures showing deficits equivalent to 0.01 per cent of the NHS
budget as a horror story.
The document did not include other trust hospitals which are in surplus, Mr
Waldegrave said. The service was in balance over the whole of last year.
Later on BBC radio, however, Mr Waldegrave acknowledged 'particular problems
in particular hospitals'.
Mr Duncan Nichol, chief executive of the NHS management executive, said:
'The document is straightforward monthly management reporting.'
However, Mr Cook said the document highlighted the continued underfunding of
the health service which Labour would seek to restore if it won the general
election.
Mr Cook said, however, that NHS managers had divided hospitals with
financial deficits into 'hot spots' and 'tepid spots', while the document
euphemistically referred to bad publicity as 'noise'.
The first priority of civil servants was to 'keep the truth out of the
news,' Mr Cook said.
