FT  06 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Scope for Mid-East change, says
Hogg - Foreign Office Questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT appeared yesterday to countenance the eventual involvement of
Palestinians from Arab East Jerusalem in the Middle East peace talks, as it
called on the Israeli government to desist from commencing to build further
settlements in the occupied territories.
Mr Douglas Hogg, foreign office minister, suggested that there was greater
scope for changes to the Palestinian delegation in the context of a
multilateral forum than in bilateral sessions.
The views of Palestinians in East Jerusalem must be represented somewhere,
he said.
Mr Hogg also expressed the view that the Jerusalem government's settlement
policies were 'a serious obstacle' to progress at the talks.
Any announcement by Israel that it intended to desist from those policies
would be 'an important confidence-building measure,' he said.
Invited by Labour to respond to a statement by the Israeli Labour party that
it would put a freeze on resettlement if it won a general election in June,
Mr Hogg said that he welcomed any such statement by an Israeli politician.
He hoped that would also be the policy of Mr Yitzhak Shamir, the prime
minister, were he re-elected.
Mr Hogg's remarks come in the wake of the exclusion of Palestinian delegates
from formal deliberations at last month's multinational forum on Middle East
issues in Moscow.
The exclusions were because of a dispute over the identity of the
delegation's nominees.
It followed a decision by the Palestine Liberation Organisation to insist on
the inclusion of diaspora Palestinians in their delegation.
The government said yesterday that it was pressing for the former Soviet
republics to be admitted to the IMF as soon as possible.
