FT  06 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): Government body fails to meet training
target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Employment Service, the government agency that helps the unemployed find
work and pays out unemployment benefit, yesterday admitted that it had
failed to meet its training target.
The target, one of a number set annually by Mr Michael Howard, the
employment secretary, specified that for every 2.5 people the service refers
to Employment Training, the government scheme which aims to help the
long-term unemployed return to work, one person should take up a place. In
the current quarter, one person starts a course for every 2.9 people who are
referred.
Mr Ron Leighton, Labour chairman of the Commons employment committee, said
the gap was 'a major shortfall'.
Mr Leighton asked Mr Michael Fogden, chief executive of the Employment
Service, whether the shortfall had arisen because the number of training
places available was fewer than promised.
Mr Fogden said the shortfall could not be attributed to the number of places
available. He said: 'It is about the quality of our selectiveness and
advisory skills.'
This week the Labour party accused the government of underspending the
Employment Training budget by Pounds 70m and raiding the budget to make good
its promises on the parallel Youth Training scheme.
Mr Fogden said the figures were an improvement on the last quarter, when for
every person starting training, 3.2 people had been referred.
</TEXT>
