<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Orient-style carpet sells for pounds 33,000: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CARPET created by William Morris in about 1890 for Old Swan House on
London's Chelsea Embankment sold for Pounds 33,000 at Christie's yesterday,
slightly above estimate. The carpet, measuring 396 cm by 380 cm, was
inspired by Persian and Turkish designs of the 16th century.
It was the top price in an auction of British decorative arts from 1880 to
the present day.
A design by Morris for a stained glass window, depicting a minstrel holding
cymbals, sold for Pounds 9,350, while a Burne-Jones design, of the Virgin
Mary, for another stained glass window, made by Morris &amp; Co, went for Pounds
10,450.
Other important names with work in the auction were Charles Rennie
Mackin-tosh and Sir Edward Lutyens.
An ebonised and painted corner cabinet, catalogued as designed by Mackintosh
and painted by his wife Margaret, sold for Pounds 13,200, slightly below
forecast. There had been some doubts about its provenance.
Much of the furniture designed by Lutyens was withdrawn before the auction,
but a pair of side cabinets, in the Renaissance style, part of the interior
decoration of Heathcote, Ilkley, West Yorkshire, the first commission in
which Lutyens designed the house as well as the contents, sold for Pounds
5,500.
The biggest surprise of the day was the Pounds 28,600 paid for the Yatman
bed, designed by William Burges in 1858 in the Jacobean style as a wedding
present for his patron, the Rev J. A. Yatman. The half-tester bed doubled
its estimate.
</TEXT>
