<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): BT may impose redundancies in building
services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BT is considering compulsory redundancies in the running down of its
building services division, according to a management discussion document.
BT has so far avoided compulsory redundancies in its programme, which
started in April 1990, aimed at cutting the 220,000-strong workforce by more
than 30,000.
The internal memo now says that, to contract out more building work, an
'enabling tool' will be required from the personnel department to allow
compulsory redundancies for grades covered by the National Communications
Union, the main BT union.
BT has never formally ruled out compulsory redundancies. But it has a
comprehensive voluntary redundancy agreement with the NCU which provides for
generous severance terms.
Nevertheless, the company has been having difficulty in reaching its
redundancy targets voluntarily. It has also refused to refrain from
compulsorily retiring 4,000 male workers aged 60 or over, although the NCU
says it has improved severance terms.
The NCU believes that the 30,000 redundancy target has now been raised to
50,000. The union says the company may seek a further 18,000 redundancies
this year.
Mr Billy McClory, an NCU official, said yesterday that the pressure for
compulsory redundancies was growing and said that areas of BT that were
seeking labour, such as personal communications, were not taking it from
those which were trying to shed it, such as business communications.
Plans to shed 1,500 cleaning jobs were also disclosed yesterday. The move is
part of the effort to dispose of 'non-core' activities by selling businesses
or contracting out services.
Six years ago BT had 4,000 cleaning staff - numbers have been reduced by
contracting out and the process is due to be completed within the next two
years.
BT said that, in a similar exercise in 1990 involving 3,000 catering staff,
80 per cent of the employees involved took up jobs with the catering company
that won the contract.
BT says it is likely the cleaning jobs will follow a similar pattern. A
voluntary redundancy package is on offer for those who do not go to work for
private contractors, but enforced job losses have not been ruled out.
The Union of Communication Workers, which represents most of the cleaners,
has failed to win contracts for cleaning co-operatives.
It now fears that some cleaners may end up taking a wage cut if they work
for private contractors.
BT pay is Pounds 3.63 an hour but the UCW says it has found some contractors
paying as little as Pounds 2.50 an hour.
</TEXT>
