<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Few significant differences in prices found: MMC reports on
the car industry broadly back UK dealers but find that smaller vehicles are
much cheaper in France and Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ANALYSIS of car price differences across Europe was a core task for the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Surveys in recent years by the Consumers Association and the Federation of
European Consumer Associations have claimed that UK prices are substantially
higher than those for comparable cars in some other EC countries.
The commission concludes, however, that 'a comparison of the price ranges in
the UK with those in France and Germany, the two markets studied most
similar to the UK in size and both with substantial indigenous manufacturing
capacity, does not indicate a significant difference in general price
levels.'
That does not apply so closely to prices for smaller cars, however. The
commission says there are several model variants in France and Germany
'whose adjusted prices appear on any of our assumptions to be considerably
lower than those in the UK'.
The commission points out that prices in Belgium and in the Netherlands tend
to be below those in the other markets in all segments, with particularly
noticeable differences in the segment for small cars.
'These smaller markets, however, are affected by a number of factors,
including the Belgian price control system and the absence in both countries
of a major indigenous manufacturer. Prices in markets of this nature are
necessarily less reliable guides to the potential level of prices in the
UK.'
The commission says the results of its work do not lead it to expect
significant differences in prices between the UK and France or Germany in
the future. 'We think it reasonable to assume, however, that for individual
models, particularly in the smaller car segment, prices to private customers
in the UK will be higher than those available in other EC countries, and
especially in Belgium and the Netherlands, and that from time to time even
the general level of prices may be expected to diverge.'
The commission says that list-price differences between the UK and other EC
markets are indeed wide, but they narrow considerably when they are adjusted
for different levels of equipment specification. In addition, 'some
estimation of actual transaction prices is essential,' says the report.
The commission relied on information from the carmakers for its evidence for
discount levels and other financial benefits offered to buyers and therefore
for actual transaction prices. It also accepted that exchange-rate
fluctuations have an 'major impact on price differences at any point in
time' and accordingly made further significant price adjustments.
An appendix to the report indicates the fierce lobbying carried out by the
carmakers, in particular in response to the controversial early comparative
price research carried out for the commission by Ludvigsen Associates (LAL).
'We received criticisms of various aspects of the LAL report,' says the
commission.
'We also received serious complaints from two of the major suppliers,
Vauxhall and Ford. Vauxhall, following the recent publication by a company
associated with LAL of a report on the motor industry, suggested that LAL
had made use of the work it had carried out for us and information supplied
in confidence by Vauxhall, in a publication made with a view to commercial
gain. It was suggested that a breach of the prohibition in section 133 (1)
of the act on the disclosure of information might have occurred.'
Ford argued that LAL's apparent commercial interest in a marketing venture
whose success was not consistent with selective distribution in its present
form was incompatible with its role as the commission's consultant.
Vauxhall raised other objections, and the commission says: 'We were
therefore requested to expunge from our report all reference to the LAL work
and to base no conclusions on this work.'
LAL rejected the allegations of bias, however, and the commission backed it
up.
New Motor Cars. HMSO. Pounds 46; Motor Car Parts. HMSO. Pounds 18.85
