FT  06 FEB 92 / Businessman remanded
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A BUSINESSMAN charged over the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce
International was refused bail when he appeared before City of London
magistrates yesterday.
Mr Mohammed Abdul Baqi, 66, of Kings Langley, Hertfordshire, is accused of
conspiring to falsely inform accountants that a company owed BCCI more than
Dollars 76m. He was remanded in custody until February 11.
Mr Baqi is a former managing director of Attock Oil, an oilproducing and
trading group based in London. He is the first person to be arrested in
Britain in connection with the investigation.
It is alleged that he conspired with Mr Basheer Chowdry and other members of
the BCCI senior management to supply audit confirmations to Price
Waterhouse, external auditors of BCCI (Overseas) Ltd, showing that Attock
Oil International owed BCCI sums totalling Dollars 76,517,952 - to his
knowledge misleading, false or deceptive in that the debts were not in fact
owed.
