<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Monopoly is found in supply of parts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE commission's report into the supply of car parts UK finds that a complex
monopoly exists in favour of carmakers, but that there are no practices
operating against the public interest.
The commission says there is active competition between component suppliers
and in wholesaling to the independent sector.
However, there is still little direct competition in supply to the
carmakers' franchised dealers, in spite of the partial removal of exclusive
purchasing requirements after the commission's investigation of cars parts
in 1982.
The complex monopoly exists, the commission says, because carmakers use one
or more of the following restrictive practices in supplying parts to their
franchised dealers:
Taking account of parts sales in calculating general dealer bonuses and
rebates, which was an inducement for dealers to sell the maker's parts.
Preventing dealers from acting as distributors for suppliers of competing
parts.
Refusing to supply branded parts except to their own franchised dealers.
Withholding diagnostic equipment or related information required for
servicing their cars from persons other than their dealers.
Applying conditions that restrict the ability of com-ponent manufacturers to
supply the independent sector.
</TEXT>
