<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Death toll rises in Algeria: Demonstrators take to guns in
street battles
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIGHTING resumed yesterday in the Algerian mountain town of Batna, where
Moslem militants say 15 people have been killed and dozens wounded in
two-days of clashes with troops and police.
Local security forces said eight people had been killed and 57 wounded since
the violence erupted on Tuesday. Algiers radio reported last night that
sporadic gunfire could still be heard and helicopters were flying over the
town. It added that the security forces had again used teargas in continuing
clashes with the fundamentalists angered that a Batna court had sentenced a
local preacher to two months in jail for inciting rebellion.
He was one of scores of preachers arrested in a government crackdown on the
use of mosques for political ends by the fundamentalist Islamic Salvation
Front (FIS), which won 47 per cent of the vote in last December's first
round of elections and was confident of victory had the second round not
been cancelled.
An army captain was among those wounded in Batna and the authorities
reported the first use of guns by demonstrators since last June's riots.
The incident is the latest in a string of protests which have led to running
street battles and to protesters being killed. The most serious clashes last
week were in the eastern capital of Constantine and the southern town of
Laghouat.
The FIS has called on militants to march after Friday prayers on February 14
from Algiers' May 1st Square to Martyrs' Square. The march would demand an
end to 'political piracy' which the FIS says brought a five-man presidency
to power last month in a coup d'etat.
Meanwhile, at least four bombs were thrown in Algiers during the past week.
The targets included the US embassy, the French consulate, and the Ministry
of Justice. Friday prayers in the three or four areas of the city which are
FIS strongholds (Bab el Oued, Kouba, Belcourt and Badjarah) remain tense
with an ever present risk of violence. The FIS yesterday repeated its claim
that only an an Islamic state can achieve stability.
</TEXT>
