<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Paris plans friendship pact with Yeltsin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff and AP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE and Russia plan to sign a friendship treaty to conclude a two-day
state visit by Mr Boris Yeltsin, the Russian president.
The two governments are also expected to sign a number of co-operation
deals, including an agreement to increase security surrounding the former
Soviet nuclear arsenal.
After a meeting between Mr Yeltsin and French President Francois Mitterrand
yesterday, the first day of the Russian president's visit, a French official
said Mr Yeltsin had made no specific request for a cut in French nuclear
forces, despite earlier reports that he planned to do so.
'The most important element was the great convergence of views on the notion
of defence sufficiency, of minimal deterrence,' the official said.
Following last Friday's meeting of heads of state at the United Nations
Security Council, the French government claims to have secured US agreement
for a special meeting of nuclear powers, to discuss the security of such
weapons in the former Soviet Union.
Paris has not made clear when such a meeting would be held, or whether the
former Soviet Union would be represented by Russia or by the four republics
with nuclear weapons on their territory - Russia, Belarus, Ukraine and
Kazakhstan.
France is according Mr Yeltsin high ceremonial honours during his visit.
This is partly to make up for the cool reception Mr Yeltsin received when he
last visited France, in April last year.
AP adds: Russia intends to sell or lease 50 percent of its oil production
and exploration to foreigners, a top foreign ministry official travelling
with Mr Yeltsin announced yesterday.
Mr Vladislav Sorokin, chief of the foreign ministry's economics department,
said that two laws are currently being prepared that would allow foreign
companies to take out large shareholdings in soon-to-be privatized oil
companies, and to obtain 60-year leases on exploration sites.
Royalties paid by the foreign companies will allow Russia to finance a
substantial part of its economic modernization, he said.
Alexander Mariachine, presidnet of the Neftgazstroibank, the Russian
commercial bank charged with privatizing part of the petroleum industry,
said that numerous private companies were being created to take over the
state-run sector.
The privatization process will take three to five years, he said.
</TEXT>
