<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Parties unite to play down Ashdown's affair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrat MPs yesterday rallied round Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party's
leader, after he said he had a brief affair with his former secretary five
years ago.
He also won backing from Mr John Major and Mr Neil Kinnock, who both
insisted that the affair should not become an election issue.
Mr Ashdown was forced to make the admission after the theft last month of
personal papers from his solicitors - Bates, Wells &amp; Braithwaite in the City
of London.
The effect of Mr Ashdown's statement on Liberal Democrats' election fortunes
remains uncertain. At Westminster his greatest strength was seen as
portraying Liberal Democrats as above what he regards as Britain's outdated
and unfair political system.
There have been a number of thefts and break-ins at political offices in
recent months, intensifying fears at Westminster that this year's election
campaign would be the dirtiest on record. All political parties have
suffered burglaries, particularly of computer equipment.
The Conservatives last night catalogued 37 break-ins which had occurred at
25 of their constituency offices over the last three years, including the
telephone bugging of an office in Southampton. Most involved the theft of
computer equipment. Labour last night said it was carrying out a similar
survey of its constituency offices.
There were signs from Downing Street yesterday that the government was
sympathetic to calls for tougher security measures at the Commons.
One senior Liberal Democrat official said the explanation for the spate of
break-ins probably lay 'somewhere between overt conspiracy and coincidence'.
However, Conservative Central Office said there was no reason to suppose the
incidents were anything but common theft.
Lord Holme, a colleague of Mr Ashdown, said on BBC radio he feared a new
form of civil crime might be emerging 'where people see the opportunity for
getting hold of confidential documents and selling them on to the press'.
At a meeting of the parliamentary party last night Mr Ashdown apologised for
any difficulties he might have caused. He received unanimous support from
his colleagues.
At the weekend he had taken out legal injunctions against all the main
national media outlets after Mr Andrew Phillips, his solicitor, heard that
the News of the World had been offered a copy of a note stolen from a safe.
The note was an account of a meeting in May 1990 in which Mr Ashdown told Mr
Phillips about the affair.
Mr Ashdown decided to make his statement after the injunctions were referred
to in a Scottish newspaper. Party officials said he recognised he would have
to make a statement eventually - in spite of his belief that the affair
should remain a private matter.
Within minutes of his statement, Mr Major said: 'These matters are not
relevant to Mr Ashdown's policies or his capabilities. They should not be a
political issue.'
Mr Kinnock said: 'His private life has nothing to do with the political
issues that face the nation.'
