<HEADLINE>
FT  06 FEB 92 / Car industry report attacked as 'sell-out'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS and KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Monopolies and Mergers Commission report on new car sales in the UK was
condemned yesterday as a 'sell-out' by the Consumers' Association, and was
greeted mostly with relief by motor manufacturers and dealers.
The 1,000-page report, published yesterday, concludes that consumers,
particularly private motorists, pay more for their cars than they should,
and proposes a range of measures to increase competition.
It also finds there is a complex monopoly involving 24 carmakers and
importers, and a number of restrictions imposed by suppliers on their
dealers which operate against the public interest.
In spite of these findings, the report largely absolves carmakers and
dealers of profiteering and effectively rejects consumer group calls for the
current system of exclusively franchised dealers to be scrapped in favour of
a market 'free-for-all'.
Mr Peter Lilley, trade and industry secretary, acknowledged that the MMC had
examples of cars priced 'significantly lower' in some continental European
countries than in the UK.
Nevertheless, 'a comparison of the price ranges in the UK with those in the
markets most similar to the UK - France and Germany - did not indicate
significant differences in general price levels', he said.
Mr Lilley, who has had the report for three months, said that before taking
any decisions he wanted to hear the views of motorists, dealers, importers
and carmakers.
But with the consultation period lasting until April 3, government action is
unlikely before the general election.
Most significantly Mr Lilley said yesterday the government would be
considering whether the UK should remove all restrictions on Japanese
vehicle imports before the end of 1999, the date agreed last year by the
European Commission and the Japanese Ministry for International Trade and
Industry for full liberalisation of the EC new car market.
A voluntary export restraint (VER) or gentleman's agreement, in existence in
the UK since 1975, has effectively limited the share of Japanese imported
cars to about 11 per cent of the UK new car market.
This restraint must be terminated by the end of 1992 under the terms of last
year's EC-Japan accord, but will be replaced by an overall VER for the whole
of the EC.
There will be no limit on Japanese production in Europe, however, and the
share of Japanese makes in the UK is widely expected to more than double
during the decade.
The MMC report says that on competition grounds alone the restraint should
be removed as soon as possible.
The Consumers' Association claimed UK motorists would still be paying up to
Pounds 3,000 more than they should for a new car, in spite of the report's
conclusion that there was a complex monopoly.
'It still hammers motorists,' said Dr John Beishon, the CA's director,
adding that 'the only people to gain from it are car manufacturers, dealers
and company car buyers'.
However, the Retail Motor Industry Federation said the report demonstrated
that the motor trade was 'the most price-competitive area of consumer goods
retailing in the UK economy'.
Report details and analysis, Page 6
Editorial comment, Page 20
Motor industry breathes sigh of relief, Page 20
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
